//main
Definition :
//adverb.yes
Yes>
Used to give a positive answer or reply to a question, request, or offer; used to give an affirmative response.
//adverb.no
No
Used to give a negative response; the opposite of yes. The movement is sometimes once, sometimes twice, sometimes plural, depending on the contexts. 
>
//alphabets.A
A
The first letter of the English alphabet, a vowel. Not to be confused with the letter "S". The thumb should be on the outside, not on the closed fingers. 
//alphabets.B
B
The second letter of the English alphabet, a consonant. 
//alphabets.C
C
The third letter of the English alphabet, a consonant. 
//alphabets.Y
Y
The 25th letter of the English alphabet, a consonant. 
//attachments.like
Like
Other similar words such as good, approve, etc. The hand is showing a thumbs up.
//attachments.dislike
Dislike
Other similar words such as bad, disapprove, etc. The hand is showing a thumbs down.
//attachments.iloveyou
I Love You
 Used to express "I Love You" in different contexts. The ILY handshape is a combination of the three fingerspelled letters: I+L+Y (I Love You). It is used to, often informally, express "I love you" among family members, as well as sometimes among very close friends, whenever appropriate. It can be used at parting, or used as a different meaning in contexts. 
//numbers.num1
1 (One)
The lowest cardinal number; half of two; the numeral symbol of 1. Palm in for the cardinal number. Note, palm out for age, address, phone number, and some others. 
//numbers.num2
2 (Two)
Equivalent to the sum of one and one; one less than three; a symbol for this number as 2 or II. The orientation of the palm faces the signer for a number, but faces the listener for two o clock and age. 
//numbers.num3
3 (Three)
The number three. The palm facing the signer is generally used in cardinal number.
//pronouns.me
I (Me)
The ASL signs/words "I" and "me" are the same. It is a pronoun. The object or subject of the pronoun can be identified in sentence structure.
//pronouns.you
You
The pronoun of the second person singular, used of the person being addressed.
